This game is a drama unfolding from the perspective of an eight-year-old [i]little lady[/i]. The artwork, the sound, the whole atmosphere is exceptional. For me, at least, it has enough sarcasm to make it funny, even though it's a grim story.

The gameplay is simple and linear, but it works. After doing the first run, I've played it again, choosing all the alternative options (as far as I could remember). On the third run, I've checked some guides to get the remaining achievements. All in all, the whole three runs took me about 11 hours. Would I play it again? I think not. Did I get bored playing three times almost the same game? No, there are little things that you discover each run. There are games that I wouldn't want to play them again, most of them are too tedious, too much investment for too little extra, this one was entertaining. 

It's not a perfect game by any means:
- as far as I could observe, all the Q&A with Mr. Voice are useless, there is no change whatsoever in the story line;
- the alternative actions do add to the fun, but most of them* don't change any future scenarios (*except for the fish and the dog), they don't really change the end game, there's no alternative ending based on any of the decisions you make.
From one perspective, I guess it works for this fatidic story: no matter what you do, you can't change your fate, you can't change the end game. Still, I just find it odd to put our minds to work to decide on something that has no value, that's [i]unfortunate[/i].
- Steam Cloud doesn't work on GNU/Linux.

I've bought the whole Fancy Edition on sale, and I think it was worth all the money:
- great visuals, great sound, nice story;
- there is some replay value, just enough to push the game time around 10 hours (about three hours per run);
- no 3rd party EULA where you accept to sell your soul to the devil, just because game companies want to gather and/or sell your data; game companies should be making and selling games, not gathering and/or selling users' data. The Steam EULA covers most problematic cases a company needs;
- native support for GNU/Linux;
- Steam Cloud (there is a bug with Steam Cloud saves on GNU/Linux, unfortunately, better run with Proton for playing on multiple machines).

To wrap it up, I think this is one of the nicest games I've ever played. With all its caveats, I still recommend it to everyone. There are lessons to be learned from any story, and this game story offers many subtle lessons. [i]Yikes forever[/i]!
